dY89R3lPyd0.title: 39 Weeks Pregnant - FALSE LABOR, Self-care, Audiobooks Recommendations
dY89R3lPyd0.description:
Did you know that FALSE LABOR is a thing?! I sure did not!

The final stretch started rough - I woke up in the middle of the night with contraction, thinking that "this is it". 12 hours later, it just stopped.

I was dumbfounded, angry and confused all at once. 

Throughout my pregnancy, I've been practicing hypnobirthing. One of the key element of this practice is to trust your body. So I put myself back together, focus on self-care, read audiobooks and did all of the nice things as I continue on this pregnancy journey. The 39th week has been a huge learning curve, and I continue to feel thankful for the opportunity to experience everything.

t9P6kb5V_6M.title: 10 LESSONS from 10 YEARS of Solo Travels
t9P6kb5V_6M.description:
10 years and over 60 countries later, here are the 10 biggest lessons learned.

10 years ago I was getting ready to leave on an open-ended trip into the unknown. I'd quit my corporate job, ended my lease (and relationship), parked the domain for this blog, and bought a one-way ticket to Bangkok. A couple months later, I'd embark on the journey that I'm still on today. 

10 years and over 60 solo countries, many laughs, tears, zip codes, friendships, loves, and losses later, I sit here in awe of the past decade. It taught me more about myself and the world than anything else could have. It was a far greater education than 16 years in school had been. 

Read more on the blog:

gqKd8VGnULs.title: 34 Weeks Pregnant Week in My Life - Nesting, Maternity Shoot, Setting up the Nursery
gqKd8VGnULs.description:
What life's like lately at 34-35 weeks pregnant. We're well into my third trimester, finishing up my 8th month of pregnancy. The nesting has begun! We're starting to get baby's space ready, putting together furniture, steam cleaning the used Snoo and stroller we got (hope it works after?!), and my maternity photo shoot at Lake Tahoe.

We also had our 34 week ultrasound to check growth, I'm navigating staying active hiking while pregnant and doing prenatal yoga, and we put together his crib and other furniture in the nursery.

wTnBXASDZpk.description:
Idaho is the most underrated state in the US - there, I said it!

I took a solo trip to Southern Idaho, one of my favorite states to travel alone in. As an introvert, I really appreciate the solitude, vast spaces with little or no crowds that Southern Idaho offers. Follow along as I take you around waterfalls, hiking spots, solo traveler-friendly accommodations and delicious restaurant in Southern Idaho!

My Southern Idaho itinerary here ↠ https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/things-to-do-twin-falls-idaho/

PQwk9jvwJfI.title: Traveling in my Third Trimester of Pregnancy (Joshua Tree)
PQwk9jvwJfI.description:
More awesome things to do in Joshua Tree National Park: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/what-to-do-in-joshua-tree/ 

I am 7-months pregnant, and it happened to be my 36th birthday! To celebrate, Garett and I stayed in a swanky Airbnb in Joshua Tree National Park, to savor every last moment where there's just the two of us. This Airbnb was even better in real life than in pictures! From retro interior design, a full kitchen, a rock-and-roll entertainment room, to a container swimming pool with cut-out, follow us as we show you around!

g5b-0rYLfwI.title: Boy or Girl?! Baby F Gender Reveal
g5b-0rYLfwI.description:
Even other gender is not that big of a deal to us, it was still really fun to find out the sex of our baby. I went from thinking gender reveals were really stupid to actually enjoying the experience of finding out a little bit more about our little bundle of joy to be. 

I find out the results of my NIPT screening for chromosomal abnormalities, send the sex results to a friend so that I can be surprised with my family as we cut the cake to find out if we're having a boy or a girl.

AJNzyZjY-MY.title: SOLO ROAD TRIPPING in the California Desert - Joshua Tree, Painted Canyon, Anza Borrego with Toyota
AJNzyZjY-MY.description:
Solo desert road tripping with Toyota in Joshua Tree National Park, Anza Borrego Desert State Park, the Painted Canyon hike, Temecula, and more. 

I'm nearing the end of my solo travels in the second trimester of my pregnancy and soaking up every last moment of being able to have these solo adventures. This time, I'm staying at a wonderful Airbnb in 29 palms with its own hot spring, checking out the Cholla Cactus Garden, the painted canyon ladder hike, Font's Point, Carter Estate Winery, and the Walker Canyon in search of poppies. 

My adventure buddy is a brand new 2022 Toyota RAV4 TRD Off Road. We're heading down 4x4 roads to find the best desert gems in this stretch of California desert. 

Big thank you to Toyota for sponsoring this video!

wXKoAGXw9jw.title: Traveling in My SECOND TRIMESTER of Pregnancy (TEXAS + CALIFORNIA)
wXKoAGXw9jw.description:
Traveling while pregnant - Would you do it?!

My first trimester was difficult. I spent most of my time on the couch, and wondered if this was how I'd be the entire pregnancy now. As a full time travel blogger, it was worrying.

When my 14th week arrived, it felt like as if a new wave of energy came over me. I was excited to explore again!  At 20-week pregnant, I worked with Texas local tourism board and explored Big Bend National Park, mostly solo. A few days later, my partner, G and I went on a nice baby moon in California, where we explored the Red Woods, McWay Falls and more. 

More on the blog:
How to spend 48 hours in Big Bend National Park: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/big-bend-national-park-things-to-do/

I've been traveling around the world, mostly solo, for almost 10 years now. We all want a fabulous time when traveling, but it's still life, and life is never perfect! 66Gw72bQnz8.title: How I Decided to Have Kids (Not an Easy Choice!)
66Gw72bQnz8.description:
Here's how I *truly* feel about motherhood, and how I decided to go for it!

I’m not one of those people who always knew she wanted to be a mother. I was deeply conflicted about the whole affair up until a month before conception. Prior to that, I have done a bunch of research online, reached out to parents and asked for their honest opinion, listened to my inner wisdom and faced my struggles with honesty and kindness.

It often seems like there are two kinds of people in this world – those who just know they want to be parents, and those who are strong in their conviction that they do not.

But there’s a lot of middle ground, a land of ‘I’m not sure‘ that I suspect most of us fall into. I definitely was one of them. If you are on the same boat, I hope this video helps!

If9rtbXWL6U.title: I Swam with TIGER SHARKS in French Polynesia
If9rtbXWL6U.description:
It's my version of shark week in French Polynesia, beginning in Fakarava and ending in Tikehau, two islands in the Tuamotus that are teeming with sharks (and other awesome sealife). 

Fakarava is a remote coral atoll, and it's home to some beautiful beaches and lovely people, plus SHARKS. 

First, I'm diving with hundreds of reef sharks, some of which we're doing at night in the pitch black. This is known as Fakarava's wall of sharks, and it's some of the best diving I've ever seen. 

But we did all this to build up to the big thing - swimming with A TIGER SHARK. This apex predator is one of the types that regularly attacks humans, but I'm wondering, do we have them all wrong? Do we misunderstand? We aim to get close and personal to find out. 

WATCH the other videos in this French Polynesia series: 
The Most Beautiful Island in the World: https://youtu.be/5REagGqsUeM
Off Grid on a Remote Island: https://youtu.be/lEcuKmrZ_4A
Accidentally Hitchhiking on Huahine: https://youtu.be/2VmnqqjBLXk

https://www.bemytravelmuse.com​​

7kXbyTnAC8k.title: 7 Ways to STAY SAFE when you TRAVEL ALONE
7kXbyTnAC8k.description:
My best tips on staying safe when traveling as a solo traveler! 

I have traveled around the world solo for over 9 years, and these are my very best methods to keep me and my belongings safe when I am on the road. 

Solo travel is one of the best gift you can ever give to yourself. It's the chance to be totally selfish (in the best possible way), and IMO, the best way to come back to yourself and live life authentically. If you are thinking about taking that first solo trip, make sure to watch this vlog before you go!

More safety tips for solo travelers from the experts here: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/solo-female-travel-safety/

lEcuKmrZ_4A.title: OFF GRID On the Most Remote Island on Earth
lEcuKmrZ_4A.description:
This is the Hakaui Valley on the remote island of Nuku Hiva in the Marquesas, French Polynesia. 

With the nearest continental mass over 3000 miles away, this is one of the most remote islands on earth, and the Hakaui valley cannot be reached by road, plane, or anything other than a boat or a 17km hike from the nearest town of Taiohae. 

The island itself is a full 3 hour flight from the capitol of Tahiti! 

For this adventure, I'm seeing if I can survive for 24 hours in this jungle without electricity (other than minimal solar light), refrigeration, communication with the outside world, and the basic comforts we take for granted. Here they live off the grid, mostly living off the land foraging, growing their own food, and hunting for what they eat. This is true farm to table! This is a unique opportunity to see what it's like to live off the land, to be in harmony with the environment, and to get a peek into Marquesan culture. 

I'm joining Ana and Tangy of Cannibal art for this adventure. Order Tangy's woodwork and/or book the adventure here: https://cannibal-art.com/

Order Ana's book, the story of her journey solo hitchhiking across the world: https://cannibal-art.com/collections/book

More videos about solo travel:

MJgRIY9BDHA.title: The TRUTH About SOLO TRAVEL
MJgRIY9BDHA.description:
4 misconceptions about solo traveling, and the truth behind each of them! 

Solo traveling is one of the most empowering things you can do for yourself. I have been traveling around the world alone for 9 years, and it has truly shaped me as a person. 

I know that it can be intimidating at first (and I know this from experience), people might try to talk you out of it, you might worry for your own safety, or think that you are going to be completely alone on the entire trip, so today I am busting 4 main misconceptions many have about solo traveling, and hope that this video will give you the assurance and encouragement you need!

eWvglc3ix-w.title: Truck Camping ALONE in Utah
eWvglc3ix-w.description:
This is gorgeous Utah, and I'm solo road tripping through the state, starting at the Bonneville Salt Flats. This time, I want to find the off the beaten path things in Utah that most people miss. We're visiting hot springs (including mystic hot springs), Mars outside of Hanksville, Utah, Moab for a flight over Canyonlands and Arches National Park, Corona Arch, and so much more! Plus, I surprise a BMTM fan with a scenic flight! 

I'll be spending the whole week solo truck camping in my 4x4 truck, only dispersed camping on public lands and in national forests, always leaving no trace. 

Watch more like this: 
A day in the life of a solo female traveler in SEDONA: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfnBlWMH5g&t
Vanlife in Utah's secret places: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=crHmw9fkdxc&t

This is gorgeous Utah, and I'm solo road tripping through the state, starting at the Bonneville Salt Flats. This time, I want to find the off the beaten path things in Utah that most people miss. We're visiting hot springs (including mystic hot springs), Mars outside of Hanksville, Utah, Moab for a flight over Canyonlands and Arches National Park, Corona Arch, and so much more! Plus, I surprise a BMTM fan with a scenic flight! 

I'll be spending the whole week solo truck camping in my 4x4 truck, only dispersed camping on public lands and in national forests, always leaving no trace.

iq4p_zDUJbs.description:
My solo trip hiking and camping off the grid in and around Lassen Volcanic National Park in California. This is one of the least-visited national parks in the United States, and I wanted to experience it as a last-minute, off the grid adventure. With so much national forest land nearby, I was able to find a free camping spot and spent almost the entire trip alone, solo hiking, solo truck camping, and having a solo female travel adventure.

m7o8dHPDoV8.title: I Stayed in 5 TREEHOUSES in Washington (Worth it?)
m7o8dHPDoV8.description:
We went on the ultimate treehouse road trip in Washington state, visiting 5 tiny home treehouses that all had their own unique character and personalities. 

As someone who has always wanted a doll house that she could actually live in, the idea of building my own tiny house in the trees is more than appealing! We booked not one, but five different tiny home tree houses so that we could see what it's really like to live up in the trees with the birds. Since these were located all over Washington from Olympia, to Redmond, to concrete, to Bellingham, we turned it into a road trip, too! 

Check out the full comparison of the cheapest and most expensive treehouses we stayed in: https://youtu.be/lpnUFe3ZK0Y
And the full tour of the fancy, luxury treehouse: https://youtu.be/rIqxB7Pow1c

qTl-n316A18.title: OFF GRID in a DESERT - Earthship Biotecture
qTl-n316A18.description:
Living off the grid in a luxury earth home made out of trash? Yes, it's possible! 

This is the Earthship Biotecture in Taos, New Mexico. A community of over 70 homes or 'vessels' that are completely off the grid. They get their energy from the sun via solar panels, or wind, they get their water from the rain and snow melt and recycle it four times, they generate their own heat, and can even grow their own food all within the walls of the home. 

These are all located in the desert, with full off the grid functionality and sustainable living in mind. For those who aspire to live greener, these off the grid homes are a sight to behold. Check out the full Earthship tour of THREE of these homes. 

What is it like to live in one? I spent 96 hours living in two of the earthships including the Phoenix Earthship, to find out. Read about it here: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/earthship-biotecture-aribnb-review/

Rent Kirsten's Earthship: https://www.airbnb.com/rooms/27131684
Learn from Kirsten on how to build one yourself: https://www.ecolivingmatrix.com/
Follow her on IG: @ecolivingmatrix

Watch Earthship Biotecture videos: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCMGoHTJH-ZjsKLfpWON8Q1g

Wu8-O2Okf9s.title: White Sands National Park, New Mexico EPIC Sunset and Sledding
Wu8-O2Okf9s.description:
Is White Sands National Park in New Mexico worth the visit?

The short answer is: YES! White Sands National Park was every bit as magical as I thought it'd be. It's one a few places that I built up in my mind that actually lived up to my expectations. And although it's in the middle of nowhere, and you will most certainly be making a big detour to see it, it is worth it! Follow along as I complete 5 things I want to do in White Sands National Park, and other things to do in the area, including staying in the cutest Airbnb, brunch at a cute and delicious cafe, a day hike and a beautiful spot to see the sunset.

Traveling to White Sands National Park? Do not go without reading this guide: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/white-sands-national-park-things-to-know/

oXWoM9rX4kE.title: 48 Hours in the LOST COAST of CALIFORNIA - Humboldt County
oXWoM9rX4kE.description:
This is the home of the coastal redwood, the tallest tree in the entire world. Some of these trees reach over 30 stories high, equivalent to a Manhattan skyscraper. Many of them are thousands of years old, and yet, this is known as the lost coast of California because people don't think of it nearly as often as they do the glitz of Hollywood or the fame of the Golden Gate Bridge. 

But I love this part of California, and I've been back at least eight times. The coast line is incredible, including Trinidad State Beach, Redwood national Park, eureka, Arcata, Crescent city, and so much more. This weekend journey takes you to all of these places, and shows you how we forged our dinner and ate a completely local seafood feast one night!

This is the true lost coast of California experience. 

Traveling the coast? Watch 72 hours in Mendocino and Fort Bragg: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iyIBWgrA9eU&t
Watch my favorite places to solo travel in the USA: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sQ6ttdXKoOk

-NT91wUF6BA.title: I Spent A Night ALONE in a Remote Desert
-NT91wUF6BA.description:
Black Rock Desert is one of the most remote areas in the world. You may know it as the famous home of Burning Man. But have you ever thought about what it looks like without anyone else around?

I’ve never camped out there alone, and I was both intrigued and intimidated by the idea. The Black Rock desert is over 2 hours from the nearest large town, Reno, spread across 1000 miles of wilderness. It was selected for Burning Man because of its remoteness, and its magic.

I had to know what it would feel like to be out there totally alone, so I decided to pack up and go. 

Camping alone in an established campsite is one thing, but to be totally out there alone without any services or signal is another.

But it’s just the type of camping that makes me feel alive.

FUmSnkFooQI.title: LIFE IN A MOUNTAIN YURT in ALASKA
FUmSnkFooQI.description:
A once in a life time experience watching the aurora borealis from a magical mountain yurt in Fairbanks, Alaska!

If you have been dreaming of chasing the northern lights, you'd be happy to know that you don't have to leave the country for it! During the wintertime in Alaska, with clear skies, dark skies, and high activity, you will have the opportunity to watch the sky dance!

xfaoCGKh814.title: How to Find the NORTHERN LIGHTS
xfaoCGKh814.description:
We headed to the 'Aurora oval' in Alaska’s Denali National Park the winter to see if we'd spot the northern lightanusinf all my best tactics and reaources… how did we do?

Our trip began last week with a little road trip starting in Fairbanks Alaska. There's a lot to do there even if you don't see the lights, including hot springs, an ice sculpture festival, ice caves, and more. ICYMI, you can watch it here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QPSZIPhRaz8

Denali National Park in Alaska is super crowded in the summer, but is it worth visiting in the winter? FYI, by late February, the park road is plowed further in, to mile 12.5.  This gives you a chance to see the snow-covered mountains, and maybe if you're lucky, watch the aurora borealis, aka northern lights, over Denali. 

↠ SUBSCRIBE for adventures around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse

QPSZIPhRaz8.title: We Road Tripped ALASKA in the WINTER!
QPSZIPhRaz8.description:
We traveled to Alaska in the winter... are we insane? Our first few days in Alaska were spent exploring the Fairbanks area and included a combined 7 driving hours. How were the roads? What did we find? Did we freeze?

Fairbanks ended up being the perfect jumping off point for several destinations that were an hour+ each outside of town, all in different directions. Fairbanks is located in the aurora oval as well, which upped our chances for some northern lights views.

Fairbanks ended up being the perfect jumping off point for several destinations that were an hour+ each outside of town, all in different directions. Fairbanks is located in the aurora oval as well, which upped our chances for some northern lights views. 

↠ SUBSCRIBE for adventures around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse​​​​

Intro quotes are from the movie, Camino, and Kristin Hannah.

PMBqLmXiLis.title: Why EVERY Woman Should SOLO TRAVEL
PMBqLmXiLis.description:
Solo traveling made me the braver, more confident, smarter woman I am today. I would not be who I am without having seen the Milky Way on the other side of the world, alone and enchanted.

I was a shy child, without much confidence. I wasn’t born the person who now solo hikes and has hitchhiked all around the world, I grew into her. Solo traveling is what empowered me, and it can do the same for you.

lxT5kU4JKPw.title: The Ultimate Nevada Road Trip l Reno to Vegas
lxT5kU4JKPw.description:
The most haunted hotel, car forest and open air museums - is this the weirdest road trip in America?! G and I took a road trip along Nevada's Highway 95, between Reno and Las Vegas, and encountered all things weird (and amazing) on the way. This included ghost towns like Rhyolite, the international car forest of the last church, Tonopah, Nevada and the haunted Mizpah hotel, desert hot springs, huge Joshua trees, Death Valley, and more. 

↠ Read more about the Highway 95 road trip itinerary here: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/highway-95-road-trip-reno-to-las-vegas/

a2UJBvBZbOY.title: 48 Hours in GREAT BASIN NATIONAL PARK!
a2UJBvBZbOY.description:
Two beautiful glaciers and the second highest mountain in Nevada!

Great Basin National Park is one of the least-visited national parks, but in my opinion, it is one of the most impressive for star gazing, tree hugging, glacier views, and challenging hikes. If you are in the area, watch this vlog to find out what you can expect to see in just 2 days. 

However you choose to spend your 48 hours in Great Basin National Park, be prepared for a unique experience without the millions of people that Yosemite or Zion National Park welcome each year. Please stay on trails, even to pass others, and respect the wilderness.

↠ Read more about my 2-day Great Basin National Park itinerary: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/great-basin-national-park/

UuHOKavzE9I.title: Churchill, Manitoba: It's a winter wonderland!
UuHOKavzE9I.description:
The northern lights, dog sledding, snowmobiling in Churchill, Manitoba, Canada!

If you’ve always dreamed of seeing the Northern Lights, or have seen them already and know how incredible they are, you’ll know it’s a beautiful phenomenon that gets addictive. The more you have seen them, the more you want to again!

Churchill, Manitoba was listed as one of Canada's "50 Places of a Lifetime" by National Geographic. This tiny town with a population of just about a thousand boasts 300 nights per year with the potential to see the northern lights!

Watch the vlog to see how you can plan a northern lights trip to Churchill on a budget, as well as other things to do while you are there, including dog sledding and snowmobiling.

↠ For a complete guide to seeing the northern lights in Churchill, Manitoba: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/churchill-northern-lights/

1O_hXWFCrWo.title: A real Canadian winter in Manitoba!
1O_hXWFCrWo.description:
TOP 10 CANADIAN THINGS TO DO IN THE WINTER

Talk about a real winter experience in Manitoba, Canada! Growing up in California, snowy winter has always been a foreign concept to me. For my recent partnership with Travel Manitoba, I was given the opportunity to spend a few days exploring Manitoba, and trying out various winter activities that are fun and unique. Here are my top 10 favourite things to do in the winter:

1.  Winter walks in Whiteshell Provincial Park

I got to walk on a frozen lake! The ice is so thick, you can skate, nordic ski, walk, and snowmobile right over it. Though my favourite part was hanging and hot-tubbing in the cabin at Falcon Trails Resort - what a dreamy start to the trip.

2. Turn (boiling) water into ice magic trick!

Okay, so this may sound a little bit silly, but it is one thing you can only do when the temperature is well below freezing! Watch the vlog for a silly tutorial. ;)

3.  Festival du Voyageur

A Winnipeg special, Festival du Voyageur is a celebration of history and French, as well as indigenous, culture. You will see ice sculptures, a sugar shack with maple syrup taffy, as well as actors answering your questions in character from the fur trading time of the voyageurs.

4.  The Forks lights

The area is illuminated with lights and 150 ice-skating trails in the winter, perfect for skating and hanging out at night!

5. Thermëa Spa

This place is SO GOOD! It is the perfect winter oasis. Surrounded by nature and providing a variety of saunas and pools, this spot requires a proper blog post detailing how to get the most out of your time: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/thermea-spa-winnipeg/

6. Snow Maze

 A Maze in Corn not only has a formidable snow maze to explore, but also beautiful snow carvings inside some of the hidden rooms and an ice bar, too!

7. Hockey game! 

For many, Canada is synonymous with hockey, and I for one had to experience the sport in a place with truly passionate fans. What better way than to attend a Jets game?!

8. Assiniboine Park Zoo

The seals and bears at the Assiniboine Park Zoo are rescues who were orphaned at birth and wouldn’t survive in the wild. It’s wonderful to see them swimming around above you!

9. Mercedes AMG track

Get your adrenaline going swerving around on a frozen Lake Winnipeg in a 6-figure car at the AMG Driving Academy. The intention is to spin and swerve, having a blast and learning how to drive in icy conditions in the process.

10. Helicopter over Lake Winnipeg

What a lovely way to get a bird’s-eye view of the frozen lake! A scenic helicopter ride was the perfect ending to my winter adventures in Manitoba.

↠ For more awesome things to do in Winnipeg, Manitoba: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/winnipegs-best-things-to-do/

ZJhBZVazDfY.title: 2500 PAGODAS: WHY KAKKU PAGODAS, MYANMAR IS A MUST-SEE
ZJhBZVazDfY.description:
Magical Kakku Pagodas with 2500 pagodas to explore!

The Kakku Pagodas is the perfect off the beaten path alternative to the usual Inle Lake and temple tour. Most of the pagodas were constructed in the 17th and 18th centuries and many of them have been restored after suffering earthquake damage. They are also quite the perfect backdrop for photos, so if you are a history buff in search for a unique, lesser-known place to visit in Myanmar, this is the perfect place to go!

For more information on getting there and where to stay while you are in the area, check out this blog post: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/kakku-myanmar-pagodas/

_RjBsR7J80c.title: BEST SUNRISE + SUNSET SPOTS IN BAGAN, MYANMAR
_RjBsR7J80c.description:
Where to find the best sunrise and sunset spots in Bagan, Myanmar?

Did you know that all of the temples in Bagan are, for now, completely closed? The earthquake in 2016 severely damaged many of the temples, and given how old they are, it's only natural that Myanmar would want to protect one of its most cherished archeological sites. It’s a huge tourism draw and was recently designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site, to boot.

So the question is: can you still find good spots for sunrise and sunset in Bagan? Spoiler alert: yes, you can! Just watch the vlog to find out. ;)

For precise locations and more information, READ THIS BLOG POST: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/bagan-myanmar-best-sunrise-and-sunset/

Fly over in a hot air balloon: https://www.getyourguide.com/bagan-l2499/golden-eagle-ballooning-in-bagan-t98064/?partner_id=BLZ51DF

HkA6cXGKLnQ.title: The BEST Things to do IN MANDALAY, MYANMAR
HkA6cXGKLnQ.description:
The 5 best things to do within 24 hours in magical Mandalay, Myanmar!

With a short 24 hours in Mandalay, this is how I made the most of it and did the best there is to do in the city:

1. U Bein Bridge for Sunrise

This bridge is popular for sunset, but if you want to escape the crowd, I am happy to share that sunrise is just as, if not more perfect there!

2. Kuthodaw Pagoda

The beginning of our pagoda party! Get lost in rows and rows of white pagodas that house the world's largest book at Kuthodaw Pagoda. In each pagoda you'll see inscriptions on large stone slabs in seemingly endless rows.

3. Inwa, the Ancient Capital

I loved exploring the wooden monastery, and the exterior may remind one of Angkor Was in Cambodia. There's a 10,000 kyat entrance fee, plus 1000 for the boat that takes you across to the ruins and back. Once you're there, getting around is limited to just horse-drawn carriages for 15,000 kyat. This is something to keep in mind, for sure!

4. Umin Thonse - 30 Caves Pagoda

This one was really beautiful and intriguing! Each gold-framed doorway leads to a Buddha statue inside, and the whole area has a beautiful view. 

5. Hsinbyume Pagoda

This is definitely the cherry on top. Unlike any other religious site in the world, it's open to explore, walk on, and enjoy. It also looks very much like a beautiful wedding cake (watch the vlog to see what I mean!).

3NwlJ1AnjIw.title: SHOULD WE BOYCOTT MYANMAR?
3NwlJ1AnjIw.description:
Should tourists boycott Myanmar?

This question kept me from visiting Myanmar for years, until I realized who I was really hurting by not going, and that I'd already done something very similar several times before, and so have millions of other people: I have visited several destinations with a similar situation, but with less attention from the mainstream media. 

These experiences taught me that the best thing I can do in these cases is to support the people who have no safety net. Am I hurting the Burmese military by deciding not to visit Bagan? Certainly not. But the fall in tourism numbers has hurt people like my tour guide in Mandalay who supports a family of three on his salary. 

Have you visited Myanmar, or any other countries with policies that you disagree with? Watch the vlog and share your thoughts in the comments!

L7wvUTAXU8U.title: TONGA VS. TAHITI: Where to swim with humpback whales?

Swimming with humpback whales is a life-changing experience. I have done it in Vava'u, Tonga, and French Polynesia, two of the very few places in the world where swimming with humpback whales in their natural habitat is allowed. While both were magical in their own ways, each destination has its pros and cons. Watch the video to find out more!

If swimming with humpback whales is on your bucket list, but you are not sure where to do it, this video will help you understand what to expect in both places! That being said, whichever place you end up going, it's gonna be magical.

2QEKy5YhMsY.title: 24 HOURS IN TAHITI - IS IT WORTH IT?
2QEKy5YhMsY.description:
Is Tahiti a destination worth exploring?

Wanting to make the most out of our very last day in French Polynesia, we decided to rent a car from the airport and explore the island of Tahiti!

Accommodation:
We stayed at Fare Nukumai, an affordable local pension and I'd recommend it: https://www.booking.com/hotel/pf/fare-nukumai.en-gb.html?aid=384670

Food:
We had an amazing dinner at Lani's BBQ - portion was huge and taste was great!

Car Rental:
We rented a small car from Tahiti Easy Car, which cost about $85. I'd recommend renting a 4x4 instead, so you can get to the cool spots.

With just a few hours, we went to Maraa Grotto, which is beautiful and accessible. However, it was completely blocked! We drove to Teahupo’o, one of the world's most famous surf breaks, before backing track to Faarumai waterfall, which is free to visit and not much of a deviation from the route. They look best after rainfall. Our final stop was Papenoo Valley, where most people would book a 4 x 4 tour to see, as it’s not possible to get very far unless you have a 4 x 4 vehicle. 

So was Tahiti worth exploring, or are you better off spending your time elsewhere? Watch till the end to find out!

For a complete list of things to do in Tahiti, check this blog post out:

cP5z0uo-98o.title: Hidden Island Paradise in French Polynesia
cP5z0uo-98o.description:
What's the most beautiful Island in French Polynesia? 

Most people go to Bora Bora or Tahiti, or even Rangiroa, but I found something even better. 

This atoll is known for shark diving, Manta rays, and one long stretch of island that is so thin, you can see from the Pacific to the lagoon just by turning your head. Under 900 people live there, and it's perfect, with one of the most beautiful beaches I've ever seen!

Watch to see if you can catch the name!

Many Thanks to Matthew Reichel of Inertia Network for the drone shots: https://inertianetwork.com/

xGnCb76Kn2s.title: Swimming with WHALES in French Polynesia
xGnCb76Kn2s.description:
This experience changed my life.

Swimming, freediving and dancing with whales around a secret island in French Polynesia is an experience I will never, ever forget. These gentle giants are elegant, intelligent and loving, and we were so blessed that a group of them chose to spend hours with us. We even got to see them breaching a few times! 

The island feels like Eden, where the fishermen only need lines and spear guns, and the fruit trees are beyond prolific. I watched the locals of all ages perform Tahitian dancing at church (shown in the vlog). There must be at least a hundred families there for the event. It’s not for tourists, and there aren’t many at all, but I’m welcome and it feels good. This whole island feels good. It’s like I’ve been searching for it my whole life.

I hope you don’t mind, but I’ll never name this place. If you find it, you’ll know why. If you are trying to plan a similar trip, the best months to swim with whales in French Polynesia are between mid-August to October. I am also leading 2 small groups of women to do the exact same thing next September. The trips are now sold out, but you can join the waiting list here: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/french-polynesia-whale-swim-trip/

QbKqMVKwVdk.title: THE PERFECT INSTAGRAM PHOTO FROM START TO FINISH
QbKqMVKwVdk.description:
How I take my Instagram photos from start to finish!

I have been working at Instagram for about 7 years now, growing my account from 0 to over 119,000 followers with creative photos from my travels around the world. 

One of the most asked questions I receive is "how do you take Instagram photos, especially if you are traveling solo?". In this video, I will show you how I plan my shoot before my travels, how I get creative with my wardrobe to make myself pop in my photos, how I set my camera up to take advance selfies, or ask for help from others strategically, and finally, how I edit my photos for the gram!

1. Research: I always begin my research on where my photos are going to end up - Instagram. By searching the geotag, I get to see the color palate I will be working with, and get some cool photo ideas. I do the same on Pinterest, and often get ideas on where to go and what to do in the area!

2. Pack Accordingly: As I am almost always in my photos, I try to match my outfits with my surrounding! It's fun to get creative and play dress up.

3. Survey Your Surrounding: Even though you've done your research, get creative and think about ways that you can do something totally different than what you’ve seen before.

4. Work it: In this video, I showed you how I took 3 of my photos - #1 was the breakfast photo with a stunning view at the back, #2 was a photo on a hilltop after walking along the Path of Gods for an hour, and #3 was a sunset photo! I used different techniques (tripod, asking a stranger, and using my surrounding to place my camera strategically) and the results were awesome!

5. Post production:  I can guarantee you that 99.9% of all of your favorite photographers edit their photos, the vast majority of whom are using Lightroom. In the last part of this video, I demonstrated how I edited my photos to make them pop for the gram.

I hope you enjoyed watching this video! For more tips on taking awesome photos for Instagram, check out my blog post here: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/how-to-take-good-instagram-photos/

DPtQQXvRoaE.title: THIS IS IDAHO?! - THE PERFECT GIRLFRIEND ROAD TRIP II
DPtQQXvRoaE.description:
Is this really Idaho?! 

Our Idaho road trip continues as we started an amazing 10-mile round trip hike to Hell Roaring Lake, a fairly easy hike but there was barely anyone else around, which we were super happy about!

After the hike, we went to a hot spring that's attached to the hotel we stayed at, Mountain Village Resort. It was the perfect place to relax after horse riding and hiking. We ended the day with an amazing, healthy meal at Glow Cafe, and a nice stroll in the area. 

The next day, we continued our journey with yet another gorgeous hike, but not before some healthy breakfast at Maude's Coffee and Clothes - yes this coffee shop is also a thrift store! we hiked from the trailhead of Fox Creek and branched off to Chocolate Gulch. It’s about a 5-mile loop and it’s relatively easy with gorgeous views as the payoff.

On our last morning, we stopped by Craters of the Moon National Monument and Preserve for some dramatically different landscape to everything we have seen on the trip so far. Although this detour would require you to go back on yourself if you’re headed back to Boise, it’s worth the extra time if you can squeeze it in.

We hope you enjoyed following along on our road trip! Comment below if you are as surprised by how cool Idaho, or if you have any questions!

For a complete Idaho road trip itinerary (with stops that are not included in this vlog), check this blog post out: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/idaho-road-trip-itinerary/

h_ZdVL1VIOk.title: CORON ISLAND HOPPING: HOW TO DITCH THE CROWDS!
h_ZdVL1VIOk.description:
How to go island hopping in Coron without the crowds!

Coron has blown up in popularity over the last few years, so going on a group island hopping tour means sharing the space with many other tourists. I wanted an island hopping excursion without the crowds, so a private island hopping tour it is!

I took it very slow and split things up over 2 days:

Day 1: 
1. The Twin Lagoon: One of the most popular stops in Coron. We were able to get the lagoon pretty much to ourselves for a good few minutes, as we arrived before 8am. The Twin Lagoon was absolutely beautiful and very fun to fly a drone over, but just watch out for this ONE THING (watch the vlog to find out!).
2. Keyangan Lake: This brackish lake is magical in the morning hours, but by 10am it’s packed with people. If you want to skip the crowds, your only choice is to get there before 7:30am, which can be arranged if you are on a private tour.

Day 2:
1. Barracuda Lake: My absolute favorite out of all stops! I had it to myself for a while by going in the afternoon after the tour boats had mostly moved on. It’s less popular, so to me it was more beautiful and pretty darn similar.
2. Banul Beach: I headed to Banul Beach In the afternoon, after the tours that stop there for lunch had already left. It’s a small cove with white sand beaches and though grassy and not perfect for snorkeling, it is absolutely perfect for chilling.

And there you have it, an awesome Coron island hopping tour! For more information on the fees and other cool stops around the island, check out this blog post: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/coron-island-hopping/

KzdVZdzWhXc.title: IDAHO - THE PERFECT GIRLFRIEND ROAD TRIP PART I
KzdVZdzWhXc.description:
The most amazing girlfriend road trip to Idaho, part I.

My college best friend, Paige, and I took a wonderful road trip to Idaho in June and it was seriously the best week! We both tried something for the first time - Paige hiked for the first time, and I rode a horse! It was the perfect girlfriend road trip/getaway. Watch the video to see what went down over the week.

Day 1: The trip begins with a delicious brunch at Lemon Tree Co. at Boise, Idaho. We checked out some REALLY cool murals and took a bunch of photos and videos. The weather was amazing, and the vibe was awesome. Next, we had vegan donuts at Guru Donuts before dinner - we are on team dessert before dinner! Dinner was at Juniper. Again, everything was delicious, and we were both happy to start off the trip with a happy belly.

Day 2: We drove to Kirkham and Bonneville Hot Springs. We had such a relaxing time. Next, we made our way to Stanley and went stand up paddleboarding (Paige's first time) on Redfish Lake. We ended the day with a beautiful sunset by the river.

Day 3: Horse day! It's Paige's favorite thing to do, and it was facing a fear for me! I am still slightly terrified of horses, but our guide, Maddie, was totally awesome, and my horse for the day, Johnny was beautiful. We went on a BEAUTIFUL hike next, but that's for the next vlog. ;)

For a complete Idaho road trip itinerary (with stops that are not included in this vlog), check this blog post out: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/idaho-road-trip-itinerary/

yYLizXAk8PY.title: MAGICAL TREEHOUSE IN CORON, THE PHILIPPINES
yYLizXAk8PY.description:
Coron off the beaten path - a magical treehouse + Black Island!

I wanted to stay in a quiet place away from other tourists, and found the perfect place - a magical treehouse located in Busuanga, 30 minutes away from Coron Airport. The treehouse overlooks a beautiful mangrove, has an outdoor shower, and comes with the most adorable residential tour guide (watch the vlog to find out who he is!). 

Another benefit of staying on this side of the island, is that you can go island hopping at a cheaper rate! We took a private tour to Black Island, which was absolutely gorgeous and even had a cool cave you can swim in. Snorkeling was a lot of fun, so was flying a drone around the lagoons! 

If you are hoping for some quiet, relaxing and laidback time during your trip in Coron, the Philippines, consider following this itinerary! 

For more tips on Coron island hopping without the crowds, check out this blog post: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/coron-island-hopping/

3PKGOy6PoiQ.title: EL NIDO ISLAND HOPPING: TOUR A VS. TOUR B
3PKGOy6PoiQ.description:
When planning an island hopping tour in El Nido, which one is better, Tour A or Tour B?

Book tour A here: https://www.klook.com/activity/4168-el-nido-island-hopping-tour-a-palawan/?af_wid=7934&currency=USD&aid=cb0877eb0c6712d5
Book tour B here: https://www.klook.com/activity/4167-el-nido-island-hopping-tour-b-palawan/?af_wid=7934&currency=USD&aid=cb0877eb0c6712d5

I went on private island hopping tours to find out which one between the popular Tour A and the less crowded Tour B is better, to help you make a deicision, especially if you are short on time!

Tour A included 5 stops: The big and small lagoons, the hidden lagoon, snorkeling spot, Seven Commandos Beach, and Shimizu Island. I loved the big lagoon, and would highly suggest that instead of renting a kayak, you opt to swim through it. It was the best way to experience the big lagoon, in my opinion! Because it was a private tour, I was able to customize my routes and avoid the crowds. We had the hidden lagoon, Seven Commandos Beach and Shimizu Island all to ourselves for a good few minutes, which would not have been possible on a group tour. 

I paid 6000 pesos for a private Tour A. You can read more about it here: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/el-nido-tour-a/

Tour B also included 5 stops: Entalula Beach,  Snake Island, Cudugnon Cave, Cathedral Cave, and Pinagbuyutan Island. Note that because it was a private tour, I was able to reverse the route, which ended up being a great decision as we had all spots all to ourselves / shared with just a few other people! The tour is also less popular compared to Tour A, but enjoyable nonetheless. 

I paid 5000 pesos for a private Tour B. You can read more about it here: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/el-nido-tour-b/

So which tour is better? Watch until the end of the video to find out!

Book tour A here: https://www.klook.com/activity/4168-el-nido-island-hopping-tour-a-palawan/?af_wid=7934&currency=USD&aid=cb0877eb0c6712d5
Book tour B here: https://www.klook.com/activity/4167-el-nido-island-hopping-tour-b-palawan/?af_wid=7934&currency=USD&aid=cb0877eb0c6712d5

I went on private island hopping tours to find out which one between the popular Tour A and the less crowded Tour B is better, to help you make a deicision, especially if you are short on time!

Tour A included 5 stops: The big and small lagoons, the hidden lagoon, snorkeling spot, Seven Commandos Beach, and Shimizu Island. I loved the big lagoon, and would highly suggest that instead of renting a kayak, you opt to swim through it. It was the best way to experience the big lagoon, in my opinion! Because it was a private tour, I was able to customize my routes and avoid the crowds. We had the hidden lagoon, Seven Commandos Beach and Shimizu Island all to ourselves for a good few minutes, which would not have been possible on a group tour. 

I paid 6000 pesos for a private Tour A. You can read more about it here: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/el-nido-tour-a/

Tour B also included 5 stops: Entalula Beach,  Snake Island, Cudugnon Cave, Cathedral Cave, and Pinagbuyutan Island. Note that because it was a private tour, I was able to reverse the route, which ended up being a great decision as we had all spots all to ourselves / shared with just a few other people! The tour is also less popular compared to Tour A, but enjoyable nonetheless. 

I paid 5000 pesos for a private Tour B. You can read more about it here: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/el-nido-tour-b/

So which tour is better? Watch until the end of the video to find out!

tmEvQcq6GkU.title: SOMEONE TRIED TO BREAK IN | 7 LESSONS LEARNED AS A SOLO FEMALE TRAVELER
tmEvQcq6GkU.description:
Someone tried to break in to my bungalow in the Philippines.

My bungalow was almost broken into in the middle of the night. Thankfully, as soon as they realized there was a person inside, they ran away. I was not hurt nor robbed, but was certainly shaken.

This incident also woke me up and made me realize a few things about safety as a solo female traveler:

1. Know that it can happen anywhere: It was certainly not the country’s fault - bad things happen anywhere and everywhere. The same precautions should be taken wherever you travel to. I have always been relatively alert and only had 2 bad things happen to me in the last 7 years of traveling around the world mostly solo.

2. It’s usually done out of desperation: While this does not excuse the action, I can imagine that these things are usually done out of desperation - poverty is usually the main drive. I don’t know what I would do if I am in a desperate position. Putting this perspective in the picture helped me handle the situation with empathy and kindness.

3. Avoid unnecessary delays: I will not sleep with no clothes on when I travel solo anymore. I had to grab some clothes and put them, which really delayed any opportunity to protect myself. If you need glasses to see, I suggest putting them within reach as well.

4. Travel with a personal alarm / door jam: Have something that would help you make loud noises to let others know that you are in distress, or pack a door jam with you in your travels. 

5. Whenever possible, stay off the ground: It’s much more difficult to try to break into a room that’s high up! If you are staying in a hotel, try to ask for a room that’s above the 2nd level. This will make you a less likely target.

6. Self defense: Pick up self defense skills and PRACTICE them! You will never know when skills like this would come in handy. There are many tutorials available online. The one I watched in this video is from: 

7. Adhere to your own rules: the both times bad things (sexual assault and snatch theft) happened to me, were when I broke my own rules by walking alone at night and by not clasping my bag to secure my belongings. I'm not totally victim blaming myself here, but am saying to always watch out for yourself and avoid getting into a risky situation!

0iNlBNR9PGE.title: SOLO IN THE PHILIPPINES: ROMBLON ISLAND HOPPING TOUR
0iNlBNR9PGE.description:
A solo adventure in the Philippines - Romblon Island hopping tour!

I went on a private island hopping tour around Romblon Island and had such an amazing time! Besides the famous Bon Bon Beach, my guide took me to 4 other cool spots:

1. Bon Bon Beach: Bon Bon Beach sandbar is Romblon Island’s most famous feature. There were hundreds of people on it during low tide, so we left and came back during high tide. I recommend doing the same as the experience without too many people around was just so much better!

2. Tiamban Beach: This beautiful beach was decorated with palm trees, white sands and crystal clear water! It's great for relaxing and soaking in the calm water.

3. Logbon Beach: The Logbon Pool forms during certain time of the year, which I was not able to see in April, but it was great for snorkeling. Like Tiamban Beach, the water was calm and crystal clear.

4. Marakay Marakay Island Diving Board: If cliff jumping is your thing, be sure to make a stop at the Marakay Marakay Island Diving Board! You will see many local kids climbing and jumping off the cliff, so join the party!

5. Tinagong Dagat: Apart from Bon Bon, Tinagong Dagat was one of the things I wanted to see most during my Romblon Island hopping trip. I loved soaking in the water surrounded by cool rock formations! You will need flip flops or water shoes for this one, as the rocks are sharp.

For more information on how to get to Romblon Island, where to stay and other activities on the island, check out my full guide to Romblon Island here: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/romblon-island-hopping/

JlPzBZWl1kc.title: GETTING TO ROMBLON ISLAND - PHILIPPINES SECRET PARADISE
JlPzBZWl1kc.description:
How to get to Romblon Island in the Philippines?

I flew from Los Angeles, USA to Manila, the Philippines and began what turned out to be a 5-day long journey to Romblon Island with endless local flights, boats, jeepney, and tricycle rides. It is not easy to get around in the Philippines, but as you can see in the video, it was absolutely worth it!

In order to reach Romblon Island, you’ll first need to get to the Romblon province. You can do this by flying from Manila to Tugdan Airport in Tablas (TBH) and taking a jeepney, trike, or van to San Agustin. Cebu Pacific operates this flight 3 days per week.
 
You may need to overnight on Tablas in order to take a pump boat over. They leave daily at 8am and 1pm from San Agustin and cost 100 pesos plus a 10 pesos terminal fee. I stayed on Tablas Island for a couple of nights and it was a great, relaxing break before I continued on my journey to my final destination, Romblon Island.

Alternatively, you can fly into Caticlan Airport, ferry from Caticlan to Odiongan, and take a jeepney from there to San Agustin. It’s also worth seeing if you can go directly from Odiongan to Romblon Island, as some ferries on some days of the week stop in Odiongan on the way, like Montenegro Lines. 

You can also ferry from Batangas, which is 3 hours south of Manila by bus. This is a long option but it’s the cheapest.

If you are planning a trip to Romblon Island, be sure to bring ample cash with you - sometimes the ATM on the island might not work! For more information and a complete Romblon Island hopping itinerary, check this post out: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/romblon-island-hopping/

Zk3OrMDa87Q.title: Swimming with WHALES in TONGA
Zk3OrMDa87Q.description:
WANNA DO THE SAME (but in French Polynesia)? Join me next September: eepurl.com/dEXn2r 

Swimming, snorkeling and freediving with whales and dolphins in Tonga. 

Swimming with whales in the wild and open has been a long-time dream of mine. The whales usually start to show up in late July to early August and stay until mid-October. It’s hard to pick a sweet spot within that timeframe as any week has the potential to have tons of whale sightings, or not. Some days will be packed with whale swims while others might only have one or none. Humpback whales are wild animals and since the boats don’t feed or coax them into interactions, there are never any guarantees.

We definitely got lucky, though! Seven of us headed out on a speed boat off of the island of Vava’u, Tonga, and we were one of only 10-15 boats out on the water that day, and each of the six days that we spent swimming with the whales. We hung out with a mother whale with calfs, singing male whales, and witnessed a couple of heat runs, led by a female in heat and involving several male whales all vying for a chance to mate with her. Not only did we swim with several whales, but four dolphins as well! The trip finished with a beautiful swim in a crystal clear cave full of tiny, glittering fish.

I’m forever changed after this experience. CLICK HERE to read more about my experience and how you can book, prepare and get the most out of your trip: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/tonga-whale-swim/

Partial footage credits: Matt Reichel and Karim Iliya of Dance With Whales

rg2NKYMUxEs.title: Backpacking ALASKA: 8 Days off the Grid
rg2NKYMUxEs.description:
BMTM Adventures tours in Alaska, backpacking with 12 women and 2 other guides in Alaska's Talkeetna mountains. 

As part of my women's travel blog, I offer adventure tours around the world. For my second tour ever, we headed to Alaska for 8 full days of backpacking in the Alaskan backcountry. This meant no trails, no other people, guiding entirely by a map and compass, and carrying all of our own food and gear for the entirety of the trip. 

Many of the women who came on the trip had never backpacked before, and we were about to head out on the adventure of a lifetime. 

We saw moose, elk, so many sunny and gorgeous days, and thoroughly enjoyed the midnight sun. 

Backpacking in Alaska isn't something you ever forget. It's challenging (with river crossings and bush whacking!) but it's SO worth it to get so far away from civilization that you never see another plane, car, person, power line, or manmade structure. We spent 8 days immersed in some of the most wild nature on planet Earth. Welcome to the Last Frontier!

READ MORE about our trips and join us backpacking in Iceland in July on a trail that NatGeo rates in their top 20 in the WORLD, and/or adventure with us unda da sea in Galapagos this coming October. These are women's adventure trips open to women of all ages and backgrounds around the world: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/tours

ceSDPyPn-BI.title: 9 Days Hiking Patagonia's O Circuit
ceSDPyPn-BI.description:
Hiking the O in Torres del Paine National Park in Chilean Patagonia!

On this episode I'm taking you behind the scenes of the women's tour I led in Chilean Patagonia in March. It was just 16 women, my co-guide and me, and the amazing nature in Patagonia. 

The O Circuit in Torres del Paine National Park in Chile is easily the most famous trail in Patagonia. Though the towers in the park earned it such renown, it’s the ever-changing landscape on each day of the trail that has made me fall in love with it enough to hike it twice. My first time, I backpacked it carrying all of my own gear. The second time, I brought a group of 16 women with me and had a more luxurious experience.

Each day brought something new from hiking to Seron, Dickson, Los Perros, to the John Gardner Pass, Paine Grande, Frances, Los Cuernos, and finishing with the famous towers for sunrise and the Hotel Las Torres for a couple of days. We hiked over 80 miles with women from all around the world and of many ages, professions and backgrounds. It was an awesome trip with amazing people that I'll never forget! 

Join us this summer to backpack in Iceland: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/womens-iceland-trip/
Or surf, snorkel, and kayak in the Galapagos: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/womens-galapagos-trip/

Read more about the tours here and keep in touch for future announcements: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/tours/

hJo66Pb9Tes.title: The BEST Idaho Hot Springs
hJo66Pb9Tes.description:
Where are the Best hot springs in Idaho?

Here's the blog post with the full itinerary: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/idaho-hot-springs/

I went on a little road trip last week to find the best of the best hot springs in Idaho, beginning in Boise. The objective was simple: Soak is as many beautiful places as possible and find the best ones. It was a smashing success. Here's where we went:

Idaho City Hot Springs: A nice big pool, private jacuzzis, and even a steam bath. This one isn't a natural one and you do have to pay to use it but it's a nice stop between Boise and Stanley.

Kirkham Hot Springs: A popular one in Idaho, it's pretty nice in the winter months when there are fewer people around. This hot spring features waterfalls and a bunch of different pools and best of all, it's nice and HOT. 

Mountain Village Resort Hot Springs: The first stop in Stanley, Mountain Village has its own little barn hot spring that you can use when you stay at the hotel. 

Boat/Boater Box hot springs: This little tub on the river is adorable and a nice little place to soak. 

Sunbeam hot springs: My personal favorite, this hot spring is so nice and hot and it's also the only one I had all to myself! It's just 10 minutes down the road from Boater box. 

Goldbug Hot Spring: Idaho's most famous but for good reason. This one requires a 2-mile hike in and you get rewarded with hot springs of various temperatures and an incredible view. 

For more hot springs that weren't featured in this video along with a map and suggestions on where to stay, read the blog post: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/idaho-guide/

crHmw9fkdxc.title: Vanlife: Utah's SECRET Places
crHmw9fkdxc.description:
Taking a camper van around Southern Utah with Bearfoot Theory's Kristen Bor

I met up with fellow blogger and fellow Kristen in Utah for a week of adventures in her sick Sprinter van. Kristen has been living the #vanlife for years and she invited me along for a week of adventures with zero plans and obligations. This is what we randomly decided to see:

Dead Horse State Park outside of Moab, Utah. It's amazing in the winter with snow, and you can apply for a drone permit in the winter months! 

From there we made our way south past the Needles Overlook of Canyonlands National Park down to a personal favorite of mine, Valley of the Gods. 

Each night, we camped in BLM (Bureau of Land Management) spots like this where camping is free provided you leave no trace and are cool with having no facilities. 

From there we headed into Arizona for Canyon de Chelly, and back up towards Natural Bridges National Monument, stopping for the night at an incredible overlook that was once again BLM land. 

Next we ventured through Hite in Glen Canyon and onwards to Goblin Valley state park and Little Wild Horse Canyon. Since it looked like rain we skipped the entire slot canyon and headed to the Temple of the Sun and Moon at Capitol Reef National Park. 

We managed to spend almost the entire time without seeing any other people in Southern Utah's Secret, off the beaten path places. It made for an incredible week of adventures. 

Find my American Southwest Road Trip itinerary with many of these stops here: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/american-southwest-road-trip-itinerary/

Find Kristen's blog here: https://bearfoottheory.com/

8jEH6He34t4.title: SOLO ROAD TRIP in California's Beautiful Deserts
8jEH6He34t4.description:
A Road Trip through the California Deserts

Stops include the Alabama Hills, Death Valley, Mojave Desert, and Joshua Tree. 

We start off leaving LA bound for the Alabama Hills, which is a famous location for shooting movies and old Western flicks in California. I haven't watched a movie outside of a plane flight for 5 years so I was more interested in the arches!

From there I made my way to Death Valley and caught the sunset at the Artist's Palette, followed by the sunrise at Zabriskie Point and a hike through the Golden Canyon, followed by stargazing at the salt flats in the Badwater Basin. 

Next I made my way to the Mojave National Preserve to check out the lava caves and climb up the Kelso dunes. This is the largest protected area in the US with more Joshua trees than Joshua Tree itself! Next I hiked the Amboy Crater with Jessica Dacey with the Mojave Desert Land Trust to who shared some helpful info about taking care of the fragile desert as hikers and campers. 

Finally, I finished at Joshua tree with an epic sunset. 

If you want to visit all the deserts, I highly recommend checking out the Anza Borrego desert as well!

qKxAGHxIa44.title: The Best Christmas Markets in Germany
qKxAGHxIa44.description:
The BEST Christmas markets in Southern Germany's Baden-Württemberg.

↠ SUBSCRIBE for solo travel advice around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse

↠ CONNECT WITH ME: 
https://www.bemytravelmuse.com
Instagram : https://www.instagram.com/bemytravelmuse
Facebook : https://facebook.com/bemytravelmuse

Come with me as we explore the best Christmas markets in BaWu, including:

My favorite little town in Germany - Tübingen. When I imagine fairy tales and my inner six year old dreams about the 'olden days' I can't imagine a more perfect example than this university town in Germany's Baden-Württemberg. Each year they host the biggest chocolate market in Europe - chocolART. They've got chocolate in every imaginable form - hot chocolate, spicy, chocolate covered fruit, chocolate mulled wine, chocolate EVERYTHING. I was also completely delighted by the light-up buildings at night. 

The medieval market in Esslingen - think handmade wares, a feeling of being transported back in time, and on-theme games and eats. 

The Königlicher Weihnachtsmarkt at Hohenzollern castle! Steaming hot punch, bubbles, and baubles - What’s not to love? 

The amazing Christmas market at Ravennaschlucht in the Black Forest. This market takes place under a train bridge that changes all the colors of the rainbow!

Stuttgart's Christmas market, which is the biggest of the bunch with dazzling light displays, ice skating, and lots of handmade crafts and ornaments. 

Heidelberg, Bad Wimpfen, and Ludwigsburg all make appearances too! These are the best and most beautiful Christmas markets in Germany. Check them out!

To read more about them and how to get there, check out this post: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/best-german-christmas-markets/

NC-enZ3YiFo.description:
Exactly how to pack carry on only in the winter!

↠ SUBSCRIBE for solo travel advice around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse

↠ CONNECT WITH ME: 
https://www.bemytravelmuse.com
Instagram : https://www.instagram.com/bemytravelmuse
Facebook : https://facebook.com/bemytravelmuse

While everyone else struggles with heavy bags, I love the ease of walking around with my light bag, skipping baggage claim, having no worries that my bag might get lost by the airline, and easily taking public transportation rather than missing the fun of people-watching in a cab.

But can it be done in the winter? Can you still pack carry on only when you have bulky items to bring, need to stay warm, and still want to look cute doing it?

YES you can! Using the techniques in this video, I show you how to use a packing cube and layering to go carry on only, even in the winter! Pack like a minimalist with ease. 

Even in cold, sub zero temperatures, I teach you how to pack light quickly and super easily. 

For an easy packing list and the items from this video, read the blog post: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/how-to-pack-carry-on-luggage-in-winter/

YRSOM0Sm1aI.title: An ALL FEMALE Chef Restaurant in Tokyo! Tsurutokame
YRSOM0Sm1aI.description:
An ALL FEMALE Chef Restaurant in Tokyo! Tsurutokame

↠ SUBSCRIBE for solo travel advice around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse

↠ CONNECT WITH ME: 
https://www.bemytravelmuse.com
Instagram : https://www.instagram.com/bemytravelmuse
Facebook : https://facebook.com/bemytravelmuse

Tsurutokame, an all-female Kaiseki Restaurant located in the high-end Ginza district of Tokyo, is set to change an industry that's currently dominated by male chefs. We had a life-changing dining experience at the restaurant and interviewed the head-chef, Yubako Kamohara to find out firsthand, what it’s like being a woman in the food and restaurant industry in Japan, and what aspirations she has for other female chefs who are finding their place in Japan's elite culinary scene.

Tsurutokame has earned its well deserved fame since its opening, with a current waiting list that’s months-long. Part of its popularity is due to how economical the experience is at only 10,000¥ to 16,000¥, which is unheard of for Kaiseki, as well as how varied the menu is. We devored 10 delicate dishes carefully curated by the female chefs - the menu changes on a daily basis, with all chefs working together to decide on the techniques, styles and flavors to be implemented for the night. The chefs even curated a full vegan Kaiseki menu for me, while serving the rest of the restaurant their traditional menu. They put just as much effort into my food as everyone else’s and it really showed. This alone blows me away, since many high-level chefs will simply refuse a vegan diner or any kind of special order.

Kaiseki is one of the best dining experiences one can have in Tokyo. More than a traditional multi-course dinner, Kaiseki is also is the epitome of Japanese haute cuisine and is considered the highest-level genre of restaurant in Japan. Kaiseki is not just a meal, it is an art form. If you are planning a trip to Tokyo soon, be sure to include this in your foodie list. Since it's so popular, it's best to book seats as early as you know you'll be in Tokyo.

For more information on how you can have the same Kaiseki experience at Tsurutokame, READ THIS BLOG POST: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/tsurutokame-tokyo/

GiSvWQizSp8.title: HARAJUKU - Monster Cafe, Purikura, and more!
GiSvWQizSp8.description:
A Crazy Day in HARAJUKU!

READ MORE: 

↠ SUBSCRIBE for solo travel advice around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse

↠ CONNECT WITH ME: 
https://www.bemytravelmuse.com
Instagram : https://www.instagram.com/bemytravelmuse
Facebook : https://facebook.com/bemytravelmuse

This is Harajuku in Tokyo: fashionable, delicious, wacky, quirky, and truly one of a kind. 

First up I had to get into the Harajuku girl culture and go Shopping in Harajuku. Takeshita Street houses a number of quirky shops selling colorful clothes, accessories and costumes. I especially loved W ♥ C for its amazing selection of sweaters - perfect for the fall! For someone who loves all things sparkly and unique, Harajuku is a shopping paradise.

For those with a sweet tooth, Harajuku delivers! You will find crepes with hundreds of flavor selections at places like Santa Monica, rainbow cotton candy, and customizable ice cream at Eddy’s along the streets of Harajuku. But the highlight for me was the Kawaii Monster Cafe, filled with bright colors, Alice in Wonderland-esque design themes, and colorful and anthropomorphized food. 

Finally, you can't come to Harajuku without getting at least one Purikura! It was my first time using the customizable photo booth which makes your eyes bigger and lips and cheeks redder. It basically makes you into a cartoon! 

For more things you can do in Harajuku, CHECK OUT THIS BLOG POST: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/things-to-do-in-harajuku/

What's my good morning routine and healthy daily habits that allow me to work for myself and have success as a travel blogger?

In this video I show you a typical day from waking up to going to sleep and everything in between, including how I start my day in the morning with meditation and journaling.

Then I show you what I eat to stay healthy, my cello class, pole dancing, and an exciting project I'm working on right now!

When I'm on the road, my routine can look quite different, but it still usually includes the same morning routine and healthy eating plus exercise habits. This is how I've managed to stay productive working for myself, because it can be tough, too!

0t6nHOkN1YI.title: What I Eat in a Day in Lombok INDONESIA (VEGAN!)
0t6nHOkN1YI.description:
Eating Vegan in Kuta Lombok, Indonesia
↠ SUBSCRIBE for solo travel advice around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse

↠ CONNECT WITH ME: 
https://www.bemytravelmuse.com
Instagram : https://www.instagram.com/bemytravelmuse
Facebook : https://facebook.com/bemytravelmuse

Hey guys, I'm coming out as...vegan! 

I recently switched to a plant-based diet and while it might be difficult in some of the world to find healthy, varied foods that are plant-based, in Indonesia it's delightfully easy!

This video explores all three meals of the day in Kuta, Lombok, a surfer's paradise in the south of the island. 

I start with chia pudding at Kenza cafe with a beetroot cappuccino made with almond milk. This is my favorite breakfast spot in Kuta and I love that they have vegan options including smashed avocado and scrambled tofu (for the tofu lovers!).

Next I head to the Mexican in Town for jackfruit tacos and tostadas plus horchata and tamarind juice. This Southern Californian gives these tacos a thumbs up for deliciousness and authenticity. 

Finally I visit a Javanese takeaway food stand with tempeh, rice, all kinds of veggies, and peanut sauce. It's a full meal for only $1.50! You can find this one across from Kenza in the evenings. 

While this channel is all about solo female travel, it's about making healthy choices and growing through our travels as well. I hope you enjoy this whether you're omnivorous or just want to introduce more plants into your life. 

READ MORE: hhttps://www.bemytravelmuse.com/kuta-lombok-guide/

localized.description:
Eating Vegan in Kuta Lombok, Indonesia
↠ SUBSCRIBE for solo travel advice around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse

↠ CONNECT WITH ME: 
https://www.bemytravelmuse.com
Instagram : https://www.instagram.com/bemytravelmuse
Facebook : https://facebook.com/bemytravelmuse

Hey guys, I'm coming out as...vegan! 

I recently switched to a plant-based diet and while it might be difficult in some of the world to find healthy, varied foods that are plant-based, in Indonesia it's delightfully easy!

This video explores all three meals of the day in Kuta, Lombok, a surfer's paradise in the south of the island. 

I start with chia pudding at Kenza cafe with a beetroot cappuccino made with almond milk. This is my favorite breakfast spot in Kuta and I love that they have vegan options including smashed avocado and scrambled tofu (for the tofu lovers!).

Next I head to the Mexican in Town for jackfruit tacos and tostadas plus horchata and tamarind juice. This Southern Californian gives these tacos a thumbs up for deliciousness and authenticity. 

Finally I visit a Javanese takeaway food stand with tempeh, rice, all kinds of veggies, and peanut sauce. It's a full meal for only $1.50! You can find this one across from Kenza in the evenings. 

While this channel is all about solo female travel, it's about making healthy choices and growing through our travels as well. I hope you enjoy this whether you're omnivorous or just want to introduce more plants into your life. 

READ MORE: hhttps://www.bemytravelmuse.com/kuta-lombok-guide/

C_Tikzw3QrY.title: MERMAID Training: Learning to Freedive on Gili Air
C_Tikzw3QrY.description:
Learning to Freedive on Gili Air, Indonesia
↠ SUBSCRIBE for solo travel advice around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse

↠ CONNECT WITH ME: 
https://www.bemytravelmuse.com
Instagram : https://www.instagram.com/bemytravelmuse
Facebook : https://facebook.com/bemytravelmuse

Learning to Freedive on Gili Air was one of the most amazing and challenging adventures I've tried. More than any other sport I've tried, this one is more about one's mind than physical ability. 

This week I headed to the Gilis (islands) off the coast of Lombok in Indonesia to give it a try. I took the AIDA level one freedive course with Freedive Flow on Gili Air which took place over 4 days. 

The first day was easy, but then once I got into the ocean, I realized it would be a completely different thing! At first I struggled but I kept at it. 

This is the beginning of an aquatic love affair, I can feel it! 

READ MORE: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/indonesia-guide/
Thanks Freedive Flow! http://www.freediveflow.com/
And thanks Instagram.com/dianagarciabenito for the underwater footage

tsCxoO4i6Vo.title: I was offered $10K for a NUDE SELFIE
tsCxoO4i6Vo.description:
I didn't see this one coming....
↠ SUBSCRIBE for solo travel advice around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse

↠ CONNECT WITH ME: 
https://www.bemytravelmuse.com
Instagram : https://www.instagram.com/bemytravelmuse
Facebook : https://facebook.com/bemytravelmuse

This is a different video than I usually share but one that feels too important to ignore: Sexual harassment of women online. 

Call it what you want: Bullying, trolling, someone just trying to mess with my head, but over the past two months I've been dealing with an online stalker who won't stop commenting on my public accounts, emailing me, and invading my private and public online spaces. 

Some people told me to stay quiet about the sexual harassment but that goes against my nature. In putting this video out there, I am saying no to online bullying, no to online sexual harassment, and no to staying quiet about it. 

For more resources and for the stories of more women online who have experienced similar things, visit https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/online-sexual-harassment/

M7xKFMll5u0.title: How I Fly for FREE Internationally
M7xKFMll5u0.description:
An Awesome Travel Hacking Guide to help you fly for FREE
↠ SUBSCRIBE for solo travel advice around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse

↠ CONNECT WITH ME: 
https://www.bemytravelmuse.com
Instagram : https://www.instagram.com/bemytravelmuse
Facebook : https://facebook.com/bemytravelmuse

How can you travel for free? How can you earn airline miles without having to wait forever or fly a bunch of times? The answer is by travel hacking!

I've been travel hacking for almost 2 years now and during that time I've flown around the world, twice in business class, almost for free. In each case, I just pay taxes which could be as cheap as $30, to fly from Berlin to Lima, Cusco, LA, Thailand, and back again. 

How have I done it? By using attractive signup bonuses offered by credit card companies to rack up points. These are the cards that I mentioned in the video: 

https://bit.ly/2La7gp2

https://bit.ly/2J0yL7V

You can read more about specific methods and schemes I use that I didn't cover in the video on my blog: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/how-to-fly-for-free/

Find Nomadic Matt's book on travel hacking here: https://www.nomadicmatt.com/guide-to-travel-hacking/

V9EuQocUcOI.title: SOLO BACKPACKING the Santa Cruz trek, Peru
V9EuQocUcOI.description:
Solo Backpacking the 4-day Santa Cruz trek in Huascaran, Peru
↠ SUBSCRIBE for solo travel advice around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse

↠ CONNECT WITH ME: 
https://www.bemytravelmuse.com
Instagram : https://www.instagram.com/bemytravelmuse
Facebook : https://facebook.com/bemytravelmuse

After hiking the famous Laguna 69, a hike that goes up to 4600 meters in elevation, I tackled the 4-day Santa Cruz trek in Huascaran National Park outside of Huaraz, Peru. 

The majority of the hike takes place over 4000 meters, and I decided to do it independently and solo for the benefit of the personal challenge. Could I handle hiking at altitude with weight on? Would it be crazy to do it solo?

I started my adventure in the scariest collectivo ride ever, then began a journey through beautiful valleys, mountains, peaks, and lagoons in Peru's incredible Cordillera Blanca mountains. 

Along the way I met some interesting people (and animals!) and saw some beautiful mountains. A few mishaps occurred but overall I learned that I CAN DO THIS! 

This video will help to show you what the hike is like, and even if you don't plan to do it yourself, I'm sure there will be aspects that you can relate to! 

READ MORE: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/peru-guide

_LhY_-zk3Ig.title: Drone at Laguna 69 The BLUEST Lake in Peru!
_LhY_-zk3Ig.description:
Hiking to the insanely blue Laguna 69 in Peru!
↠ SUBSCRIBE for solo travel advice around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse

↠ CONNECT WITH ME: 
https://www.bemytravelmuse.com
Instagram : https://www.instagram.com/bemytravelmuse
Facebook : https://facebook.com/bemytravelmuse

After saying goodbye to my amazing tour group, I set off solo to Huaraz in Peru for the next leg of my adventure: Solo hiking in Huascaran National Park. My first hike was the famous Laguna 69, the most popular hike in the area. 

I could see why people love this hike in Peru so much, it's an incredibly blue glacial lake that you almost can't believe is real even when looking at it in person! I climbed up to 4600 meters with my drone to fly over the lagoon and waterfall for another perspective. 

Peru hiking is phenomenal, and this trek to Laguna 69 helped to prove that! Stay tuned for more hiking when I solo and independently hike the Santa Cruz trek next.

READ MORE about hiking the Laguna 69 here: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/hiking-laguna-69/

eDBWOWJiUu4.title: Pink Dolphins & Sloths in THE AMAZON, PERU
eDBWOWJiUu4.description:
BMTM Adventures head into the Amazon, Peru!
↠ SUBSCRIBE for solo travel advice around the world ↠ http://www.youtube.com/bemytravelmuse

↠ CONNECT WITH ME: 
https://www.bemytravelmuse.com
Instagram : https://www.instagram.com/bemytravelmuse
Facebook : https://facebook.com/bemytravelmuse

The final video of our BMTM Adventures tour in Peru brings us to the Amazon rainforest, which covers 60% of the country!

First we flew into Iquitos, the largest city in the world that is unreachable by roads (one must fly or take a boat) to head 2 hours by boat upriver to a lodge in the Amazon that is completely off the grid, running on solar power. 

We swam in the river with pink river dolphins, went pirhana fishing, and saw NINE sloths! We also ziplined in the rainforest canopy and celebrated my birthday, all in one amazing trip. 

For more about upcoming tours and to reserve your spot on next year's Peru tour, check out the tours page on my blog: https://www.bemytravelmuse.com/tours/

Special Thanks to Tahuayo Lodge for sharing your footage of the pink dolphins!
